flowRoot.flowPara: Oligophlebodes sierra (8mm) Y/dkB, W-Bk/B, Lg-YB/Bk, An-med. Mtn strs, L horn-shape stone case w some heavier stones, heavy daytime drift w case. F struggle to break film to lay eggs. All daytime activity makes for good fishing. Neophylax splendens, rickeri(18mm) BY, W-motB, Lg-BY, An-lng. Faster riffles of trout strs, but ok in wrmer wtrs, splend a bit further upstream. L short, thick case w heavy balast stones, scrape diatoms and detritus from midstream rocks. Diapause leads to concentrated emergence, P swim to surface of the riffles. F may lay out of water, or drop eggs from above, but many M and F end up floating.
L Th-2 straight fwd mrgn, often mult-branched gls - Limnephilidae.

flowPara.flowSpan: Dicosmoecus atripes
(30mm) orangeR, W-mot G&B, Lg-BY, An-lng.

Mod to large trout rvrs (McCloud, U Sac). L pred-shred, 2 yr, Y w B thx, mult-branched gls, discard case when molting, drift bare. Heavy daytime drift peaks at 4 pm. Early instars live in slack margins, make veg cases, late inst move to faster waters, make stone cases. Pup mid-summer, diapause and pupation last several wks. P emerge by clumsy swimming and crawling into shallows and out of the water. F flop onto surface and struggle for a long time when laying.
Chyranda centralis
(14 mm) strwY, W-mot ltB, Lg-ltB, An-lng. Small strs, sprg crks in leaf accums. L sparse paired gls, bark case.

L tube case, mult pairs of plates on Th-2-3, sml and isolated on Th-3, lng mid&hind Lg - Brachycentridae. L enlarge case as they grow, filter particles from the drift w md and hnd Lg, or scrape from rocks. Can ride air bubbles. P swim up, emerge in open water, F swim below or flop on surface to oviposit.
Brachycentrus occidentalis (13mm) brGn/GnB, W-Wt/tan, Lg-B/Bk, An-lng.

Very large pops. Can fasten cases on rocks in up to 1 m/sec flow. Spread legs in flow to catch particles. L sqr sect plant case, don't move around much, use anchor line and rappel, pupate in place. 4 wk pupation, massed hatches. P brGn, W-B.

flowPara.flowSpan: L free living, beadlike bdy segs in dorsal view, Lg-strong, eq size, Apl-lng, strong clws - Rhyacophilidae.

Develop, pupate, emerge, and oviposit in the same cold, clear, fast riffles and pocket water. L predator, audacious scrambler on, under rocks, B silk anchor and rappel, poor swmr, good searching pattern all year before pupation. P swim to film, A escape quickly (10's of ft, even in fast water), engendering frenetic trout feeding. A day or 2 later, F crawl or swim to bottom, lay, and then simply release and drift downstream and up to surface. Fish feed actively, but less violently than during the emergence. Rhyacophila grandis (16mm), bifilas (smlr) OGn, W-G&B mot, L-B, An-med. Mtn strs. L brG/tan, P G, W-brn.

pebbles, Lg-eq, no vis gls, Apl-shrt, clws tiny, mlt hooks on each - Glossosomatidae. L can reverse in case, crawl around on tops of rocks to scrape veg matter, often molt in sync, abandon case w each molt, maybe drift, build new case. Trout feed voraciously on the drifters. L migrate to margins of riffles, glue case to rocks to pupate. Sporatic emergence (swim to surface), oviposition (dive under), but sometimes intense enough to trigger mass feeding.
Glossosoma triviatum
(10 mm) GnB, W-plTan/medB, L-B, An-med. Cold, oxygenated med rvrs (L Yuba). L tan/C, poss pinkish, P plG, W-tan.

Hydropsyche occidentalis
(14mm) BY, W-motB, Lgs-strwY/dkB, An-lng. Huge pops. Rich strs, rvrs. Somewhat bigger, slightly wrmr wtrs than
arcto

. L finer net, wht silk anchor and rappel, poss in place of behavioral drift. Pupate in or nr habitual rifs, runs. P hatch densely, drft w bot currents, inflate pupal skin w gas and rise to surface, but float under film a long time. Then take more time to shed skin and fly away. Very vulnerable and attractive to trout during the whole process. F oviposit in large numbers, let go after laying, and drift exhausted back to surface. earyly summer.

L tube case, sand or stone, rnd or sq, 1 lrg plate pair Th-2, few tiny prs Th-3 - Lepidostomatidae. L feed on veg matter (leaves, pine needles) in mod flowing woodland strs. Enlarge case when they grow, drift with case, esp just before pupation. Pup along gentle edges nr L habitat.

(10mm) B occ Y, W-B, Lg-B, An-lng. Not restricted to strs -- also in backwtrs of large rvrs, drawing trout when they emerge. L rnd sand case, esp strong drift before pupation, P slower margins, struggling swm to film, X there.

Very large pops. Pref still or slow wtrs but can inhabit fairly swift strs and rvrs. L horn-shaped cases of large sand grains. free-moving preds, targeted by trout esp during last instar. Trout still selective well after peak emerg.

9 mm) Y/dkB, W-metalic Bk/dkB, Lg-strwY, An-vry lng. Lakes, ponds, or slow, weedy rvrs, but cool. flowRoot.flowPara: L head fwd pointing, dk shield on Th-1 only, plate Ab-IX dors, no case, or stone case without silk lining, pupates in closed cocoon under stone dome (or case as prev) glued to substrate.

L head fwd pointing, drk shield Th-1-3, sligtly furry back, Wt inter-seg gills on abdo, B anal brush, Apl-longish, good clws. Net spinner, caseless, but build tubular retreats (poss sand covered) adjacent to net. Pupates in slit-end cocoon under stone dome glued to substrate - Hydropsychidae. L spin nets on rocks and wood debris along bottoms of riffles and runs to catch drifting particles. P swim to surface, emerge in open water, A dive under and lay on bottom.
L head downward pointing, veg or mineral case with silk lining, usually extends case for new instar. Pupates in slit-ended cocoon in final-instar case, glued to substrate.
L no medial-dorsal hump on Ab-I. Lack of spacing hump implies need for moving water environment, but incl washed lake shores.
L spacing hump(s) on Ab-I. Humps together with silk linings allow the L to use abdominal undulations to pump water through the case, permitting slow or still water habitats.
